-- Phase 59 Plan 03: the C `a & b == c` gotcha precedence lock-in.
--
-- In C, `a & b == c` parses as `a & (b == c)` because == is higher precedence
-- than & (see C operator precedence table). Iron inherits this precedence ladder
-- so `a & b == c` also groups as `a & (b == c)`.
--
-- Iron's Int-only bitwise typecheck (E0233) then rejects `a & Bool` with a
-- clean compile error at the `&` site. This compile failure is the ONLY way
-- to lock the precedence in a runnable test — Iron cannot execute the
-- gotcha form because the middle expression is Bool, not Int.
--
-- If the parser ever regresses and groups as `(a & b) == c` instead, this
-- file would COMPILE (Int == Int is fine) and the test would mis-pass.
-- That's why the expected error is specifically "bitwise operator requires
-- Int operands, got 'Bool'" — the Bool can only appear here if the `b == c`
-- subexpression was evaluated FIRST, which is exactly the gotcha.

func main() {
    val a = 6
    val b = 2
    val c = 2
    val r = a & b == c
    println("{r}")
}
